24/09/2010
By Alexander Christie-Miller for Southeast European Times in Istanbul -- 24/09/10
Emerging trends in Turkish society have spelled an end to "business as usual" in political life. A more urbanised and better educated electorate demands more rights, democracy and a better life. 
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan and his Justice and Development Party have been able to capitalise on these changes and seize the political centre. The recent referendum on constitutional changes was the latest success for the party's strategy of mingling conservative values with economic liberalism, a renewed drive for EU membership, and an end to the authoritarianism that has periodically undermined civil society. 
